    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-04-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-04-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="639"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d639">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/1258.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Mexican Chargé d’Affaires</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Embassy of Mexico</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-04-08">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 8, 1911</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1218.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: Gen. Don Gonzalo Luque has experienced
                    difficulties in receiving ammunition at Ojinaga, Chihuahua, due to the fact that
                    some subordinate authority of this country, probably through an erroneous
                    interpretation of the laws of the United States, prevents the transit of
                    articles intended for military operations in our country for the national
                    army.</p>
                <p>The department of foreign relations believes this prohibition to be wholly
                    foreign to the views and purposes of the Government of the United States and
                    instructs me so to inform your excellency and to ask, as I do, as urgently as
                    the case demands, that suitable orders be sent for the information of the
                    authorities who hinder the free transit of ammunition purchased in the territory
                    of the United States by agents of the Government of Mexico.</p>
                <p>My Government hopes that the Government of this country, animated as it is by the
                    most benevolent sentiments, will take into account the grave difficulties of the
                    commander of the garrison at Ojinaga, to which the Embassy of Mexico has
                    referred in some previous note, to order measures that will remove the obstacles
                    herein referred to.</p>
                <p>I take, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Carlos Pereyra.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
